This fused ring system generally contributes to a higher melting point due to the rigidity and planarity of the structure, which often leads to stronger intermolecular interactions, such as π-π stacking. The phenyl group contributes to increased melting point due to its ability to engage in π-π stacking interactions with other aromatic rings. The contribution of a single phenyl group to the melting point might be in the range of +40 to +50°C. Combining these effects, the predicted melting point increase from the base of pyrazine is +160 to +200°C.
